## Why Sentry v9 Changes Things

Sentry v9 for Next.js deprecates the `sentry.client.config.ts` pattern in favor of Next.js's native `instrumentation.ts` API. The new pattern is cleaner, better integrated with the App Router, and works correctly with source maps — once you get past one significant gotcha.

## The New Pattern

Instead of `sentry.client.config.ts`, create two files:

**`instrumentation-client.ts`** (runs in the browser):
```typescript
import * as Sentry from '@sentry/nextjs';

Sentry.init({
  dsn: process.env.NEXT_PUBLIC_SENTRY_DSN,
  tracesSampleRate: 0.1,
  environment: process.env.NODE_ENV,
});
```

**`instrumentation.ts`** (runs on server + edge):
```typescript
import * as Sentry from '@sentry/nextjs';

export async function register() {
  if (process.env.NEXT_RUNTIME === 'nodejs') {
    Sentry.init({ dsn: process.env.NEXT_PUBLIC_SENTRY_DSN });
  }
  if (process.env.NEXT_RUNTIME === 'edge') {
    Sentry.init({ dsn: process.env.NEXT_PUBLIC_SENTRY_DSN });
  }
}
```

## The Org Slug Gotcha

The Sentry wizard pre-populates `SENTRY_ORG` from your login. If your Sentry org is named "DCYFR Labs" but the slug is `dcyfr-labs`, the wizard may set `SENTRY_ORG=dcyfr` — which is wrong.

`@sentry/cli` v2 gives **environment variables precedence over plugin config**. This means if you fix the org slug in `next.config.ts` but the Vercel env var is still wrong, source maps will fail silently — the build succeeds but maps never upload.

**Fix:** Check your Sentry org slug at `https://sentry.io/settings/` and set the Vercel env var explicitly:

```
SENTRY_ORG=dcyfr-labs  # not dcyfr, not "DCYFR Labs"
SENTRY_PROJECT=dcyfr-app
SENTRY_AUTH_TOKEN=<internal-integration-token>
```

## Source Map Upload Checklist

- [ ] `SENTRY_ORG` env var matches the actual org slug (check Settings)
- [ ] `SENTRY_PROJECT` matches the project slug (not the display name)
- [ ] `SENTRY_AUTH_TOKEN` is an Internal Integration token with `project:releases` + `org:read` scopes
- [ ] `sourcemaps: { deleteSourcemapsAfterUpload: true }` is set to avoid serving maps publicly
- [ ] `widenClientFileUpload: true` is set for Next.js App Router client chunks

With these in place, source maps upload on every Vercel production deploy and Sentry errors show the original TypeScript source.
